Media notes: pair of Common Raven at Pt. Pinos, 22 Apr 2016
Observation Details: pair; first one heard somewhere near Crespi (see that list), then one seen in flight over dunes and landed in wind-bent cypress, where dive-bombed by crows. This was south of the Point, opposite the pull-out halfway to South Gull Roost. Then I saw two were in the cypress together and one was playing with a twig; then the other (larger) one flew to pull-out and walked across it to where a guy in RV was feeding squirrels & gulls, and joined in. I telephone Rita to bring the camera. But the time she arrived the raven was hidden behind the RV, so we sneaked a peak and Rita noted two ravens together there. Both were surprisingly unskittish with the mass of gulls, etc., but they were dominate, several times chasing crows away. Got a long series of photos. This is the first pair ever at Pt. Pinos

Locality: Stewart B. McKinney NWR--Long Beach Blvd. Pond
Observation Details: As I was getting in car to leave I heard this bizarre gurgling clucking call. Looked up and a magnificent common raven was making this cool call  from a tree branch above. ( I love Ravens ) I immediately recorded the calls getting a few clear ones between the circling planes and the Fed Ex trucks ugh!...so cool sounding...Then I heard a very faint and very distant common raven calling just a few times from far in the marsh.  My raven stayed watching me try to get into an optimal position to photograph him as he continuing doing his clucking calls. These calls were not loud but rhythmic clucking gurgle at odd frequencies. The other raven finally came ( about 5 min later) flying right by us calling out loudly in the usual common raven fashion, prompting my raven to follow...which he did.
Calling.

Observation Details: This bird is throwin me and friends for a loop. I am generally pretty good at telling corvids apart. I saw them fly to the dumpster and they were huge with a wedged tail. But, looking at photos, I am thinking, "are they just a larger than average AMCR who is very wet making their bill look bigger?" But, the curvature of the bill still extends more to the end and the way the feathers are washed away from their breast signify them being longer than a crows. They were also hanging alone, no one else around. But, many birds were soaked bald today. Asked some friends who also leaned CORA over AMCR or FICR. If someone disagrees though, please flag this for review, TY!

This bird is throwin me and friends for a loop. I am generally pretty good at telling corvids apart. I saw them fly to the dumpster and they were huge with a wedged tail. But, looking at photos, I am thinking, "are they just a larger than average AMCR who is very wet making their bill look bigger?" But, the curvature of the bill still extends more to the end and the way the feathers are washed away from their breast signify them being longer than a crows. They were also hanging alone, no one else around. But, many birds were soaked bald today. Asked some friends who also leaned CORA over AMCR or FICR. If someone disagrees though, please flag this for review, TY!

One seen in flight in lower BDC, and the pair with the active nest on the metal stairway on the downstream face of the BDR dam. At the nest, adults were seen coming in (sometimes both at the nest at same time) to feed their nestlings, which looks like their eyes are now open. The young appear quite alert now, begging aggressively when the adults visit the nest. They still only look like they're just beginning to get black body feathering. The young seem at that stage where they're so ugly they're kind of cute.   During one of the times both adults were down below the top of the dam an adult RTHA suddenly came into view flying fairly low over the top of the dam, heading slowly down-canyon. As soon as that hawk was seen, now fairly close to their nest, both of the adult ravens were immediately on the attack, and were quite aggressive and noisy in their effort. The hawk was quickly driven back towards the BDR side of the dam so were fairly quickly out of view from where I was watching down relatively close to the base of the dam. Their aggressiveness was impressive, being much more intense than the type of harassment CORAs might give a RTHA when, say, a hawk is circling way up overhead maybe a 1/4 to a 1/2 mile away from the ravens' nest.

Observation Details: I first heard loud, raucous calls coming from the woods near my car so I went to investigate. These calls were twice the volume of any young crows I've ever heard. They were LOUD. Not too far up the hill I found four young ravens on low-lying logs. While they were quite large they were clearly young birds - I could tell by their total disregard for me, their nonstop begging, their preening, their still slightly red gapes and their overall curiosity for the surroundings. I waited 20 minutes hoping an adult would arrive and it did, calling the classic Raven croak the entire way. By the time it arrived the "kids" had moved higher up in the trees so I couldn't see the adult, but I did see its wedge-shaped tail as it flew out of the woods. Wow, what a thrill to find this family! The light was poor which is why the photo quality isn't the best.

There was such an interesting interaction between these two ravens, perhaps some kind of courtship ritual. One would clap its bill at the other one which would meet with bill clapping from the other. Then one would bow down and flatten its wings while making hissing/huffing noises. They also faced each other and fluffed up their throat feathers. Another raven tried to land between the two, and both bullied away the intruder.  Many of the ravens in this small flock of five or six also appeared to be eating the snow.

*Important note about viewing the nesting ravens*: Virginia Rettig and I spoke to plant managers to help arrange access here for birders. It's important that birders call the control room at (609) 390-5195 to let them know that you'll be watching for the ravens. The fishing pier area and the parking lot adjacent to the raven nesting spot are both fine for viewing, but I'd recommend staying out of the way of the workers coming and going.  This is apparently the first documented nest of Common Raven in Cape May County (though Witmer Stone's "Bird Studies at Old Cape May" suggests that ravens might have been resident in the county ~100 years ago, evidence of nesting here is absent). From the appearance of the current nest site, it seems possible that the ravens have used this nest in prior years.  Two adults are regularly bringing food to vocal young (unknown number) in the large stick nest which is tucked up underneath an overhanging part of the power plant facility (see enclosed photos for the exact spot), best viewed from near these coordinates in the parking lot: 39.289335, -74.633939. Thanks to Virginia Rettig, Chris Marks, Sam Galick, and Tom Reed for helping to zero in on these birds over the past few days.

Observation Details: Un ejemplar llegó procedente del norte, venía siendo perseguido por Tyrannus melancholicus, por lo que vocalizaba en vuelo. Dio un giro y se detuvo en un pino cercano, donde después de unos minutos, entre que vocalizaba y se arreglaba el plumaje, voló a una roca y comenzó a comer de algo que estaba ahí, espantando a un Coragyps atratus que estaba cercano, probablemente una presa en descomposición. Mientras hacía eso, un segundo ejemplar apareció en la misma dirección, norte y se reunieron alejándose de la zona. En diciembre de 2023 vi dos ejemplares en Roble Negro, San Fernando, Morazán, pero no pude documentar la observación y por tanto el registro no ha sido aprobado como publico. (https://ebird.org/checklist/S155944968). Al igual que en Roble Negro, los residentes manifestaron que es ocasional verlos y escucharlos en la zona (Bailadero del Diablo, Llano del Muerto, Rancho Quemado, Sabanetas). Esta es la primera documentación con fotografías y grabaciones para el departamento de Morazán y la primera documentación con fotos para El Salvador en eBird. Hay una publicación con fotos de un registro en cerro Matarás, Chalatenango en 2019 (Ver: C. Aguirre & L. Pineda. 2020. Registro fotográfico del Cuervo Común (Corvus corax sinuatus [Wagler, 1829], Corvidae) en El Salvador. Zeledonia 24(1):39–43)

Media notes: Fledling up close
Observation Details: I arrived at 8:20 a.m. to discover the second young bird had fledged. It was on the ground across the channel from the nest. The adult was close by, cawing insistently. Within a few minutes the young bird flew back across the channel and stayed under the bridge walking back and forth under the bridge for well over an hour. It mostly jumped from rock to rock, but occasionally it would fly a couple feet. Both parents were present, at one point watching from a steel girder perch under the bridge (see photo). The adults would sometimes fly out to the trees and caw. All of a sudden the fledgling flew about 50 feet back to the nest, which I caught on video. The parents cawed and flew around frantically. In the commotion I lost sight of the fledgling but found it a few minutes later on the opposite side of the bike path close to the edge of the highway, another 50 feet or so from the nest. The parents were continuing to caw frantically. I found the fledgling had moved to safer territory in the woods and both parents were watching from the trees above, close by. I then left after almost 90 minutes of observing the process. My only question is where is the first fledgling? Or is there a possibility this is the older bird and the younger one died? The timing based on reports from other eBirders suggests this is the second younger bird and the first bird also fledged successfully.

There was such an interesting interaction between these two ravens, perhaps some kind of courtship ritual. One would clap its bill at the other one which would meet with bill clapping from the other. Then one would bow down and flatten its wings while making hissing/huffing noises. They also faced each other and fluffed up their throat feathers. Another raven tried to land between the two, and both bullied away the intruder.  Many of the ravens in this small flock of five or six also appeared to be eating the snow.

This nest site is on private property.  We decided to check the nest site to see if any birds had fledged, as this was the first return trip since March when we noted an adult bird on the nest.  The visibility of the nest is impeded this year as the entire structure was moved to a position that made seeing anything sitting on the nest impossible without literally entering the structure and climbing up a ladder.  We did not see or hear any birds on the nest.  However, as I turned around, Ben was pointing at a bird directly behind us standing on some of the structure of an adjacent building.  The bird (photos) was obviously a recent fledgling.  The plumage appeared to be good with just a hint of the down feathers on its stomach area.  The bird was hopping and doing short flights, but appeared to not yet be ready for full flight.  We quickly exited the spot after taking photos.  We heard an adult call in the distance.  A few moments later as we drove away from the nest site we observed an adult bird in an agricultural field appear to grab some kind of food and fly down to an area that we presume the adults are using to keep the new fledglings safe and teach them to forage.  We will attempt to locate the family in the near future to determine the number of fledglings this year.

In the mountains of Culberson County, Texas, Common Raven is the most common species of raven. Away from the mountains in southern Culberson County, Chihuahuan Raven is common. The characteristics of the raven pictured, which I used to identify the raven species, are: large, long heavy bill with rictal bristles extending about 1/2 the length of the culmen (in Chihuahuan Raven, rictal bristles extend significantly farther, up to 2/3 the length of the culmen), large size (compared to Chihuahuan Raven), long tail (compared to Chihuahuan Raven) and vocalizations (repeated deep, strong croaks and "knocking" calls, not the characteristic "quark" call of the Chihuahuan Raven).

A large corvid with a very large bill and conspicuous shaggy feathers on the throat was perched on a light post as I was driving across Chain Bridge to DC at 9:17 am. On my return trip across Chain Bridge at 12:19 pm this or another individual was perched on a different light post on the same section of the bridge. I parked in the small lot at the end of the bridge on the Virginia side and walked back slowly to within about 40 yards of this bird, which never left its light post perch while I was there.

Continuing.  Jim White was having his lunch at the NVF Plant Ruins in Yorklyn to see if the Raven was around.  As he was about to leave, the Raven appeared and perched on the old rusty water tower in the back of the property.  It was calling, preening, and walking around on the railing.  The bird stayed for about 5 minutes at most while I was there, then walked around the back of the water tower and disappeared.  We walked around the tower to relocate it, but it vanished. Video contains audio of the bird calling.  <iframe width="420" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/yCSyk1qeTrk?rel=0" frameborder="0"></iframe>

Jim White and I had a hunch that this bird flew to near this location from where we first located it, presumably at a carcass, along Sharpless Road, about 300 yards west of Route 82, on the north side of Ashland Nature Center.  We drove to NVF Plant in Yorklyn, and luckily saw this bird fly up and perch on the NVF Plant ruin across from the Yorklyn Post Office.  It perched and called for about 10 seconds.  I got photos, Jim got video.  A couple of the photos are below.  After the bird flew from this perch, it seemed to bank around the north side of the ruin and disappear.  We thought that it might have entered the building through one of the large open windows to perch inside.  A concentrated effort was made by us and several birders that came out quickly, but we could not relocate it.  Stakeout here tomorrow morning?

Observation Details: We soon made it to my favourite part of the day for a late lunch—Biscuit Basin. Although it was still raining, we braved it outside to make sandwiches and enjoyed them inside. However, I still stayed outside to enjoy a curious raven who claimed the picnic table in front of us. This curious raven popped its head up and walked around the table and the adjacent tree, waiting for us to finish our sandwiches to snatch them up. Behind this sentimental raven which I named Cheeto, multiple geysers erupted in the rain. The raven expertly posed in front of the geysers creating a chaotic scene. I spent a long time with Cheeto, long enough to become decent friends. We wished each other the best until we meet again and he flew up, out and over the river before he vanished into the geyser smoke. Until we meet again, buddy.

Observation Details: I first heard loud, raucous calls coming from the woods near my car so I went to investigate. These calls were twice the volume of any young crows I've ever heard. They were LOUD. Not too far up the hill I found four young ravens on low-lying logs. While they were quite large they were clearly young birds - I could tell by their total disregard for me, their nonstop begging, their preening, their still slightly red gapes and their overall curiosity for the surroundings. I waited 20 minutes hoping an adult would arrive and it did, calling the classic Raven croak the entire way. By the time it arrived the "kids" had moved higher up in the trees so I couldn't see the adult, but I did see its wedge-shaped tail as it flew out of the woods. Wow, what a thrill to find this family! The light was poor which is why the photo quality isn't the best.

This bird is throwin me and friends for a loop. I am generally pretty good at telling corvids apart. I saw them fly to the dumpster and they were huge with a wedged tail. But, looking at photos, I am thinking, "are they just a larger than average AMCR who is very wet making their bill look bigger?" But, the curvature of the bill still extends more to the end and the way the feathers are washed away from their breast signify them being longer than a crows. They were also hanging alone, no one else around. But, many birds were soaked bald today. Asked some friends who also leaned CORA over AMCR or FICR. If someone disagrees though, please flag this for review, TY!

I’ll have to check back and see if there’s any youngsters here in a few weeks.

Media notes: See entry for red-shouldered hawk for additonal pictures of the raven/hawk interaction. This is the raven returning as soon as the hawk flew off to the spot where his rabbit had been, but alas, no rabbit scraps were left for him. The bird has his feathers all puffed out, probably from the aggressive interaction.
Observation Details: A raven flew from a snag to the hillside and flew back with a dead rabbit. The rabbit appeared to be stiff from rigor mortis. As the raven began to peck it, a red-shouldered hawk attacked the raven and drove it off the rabbit. The hawk stayed on the prey, defending it from the raven, and then flew off with it. The raven returned to the site and examined the area, but finding no rabbit scraps, flew off again.

Observation Details: *First island record*   Don Burggraf's photo:

In the mountains of Culberson County, Texas, Common Raven is the most common species of raven. Away from the mountains in southern Culberson County, Chihuahuan Raven is common. The characteristics of the raven pictured, which I used to identify the raven species, are: large, long heavy bill with rictal bristles extending about 1/2 the length of the culmen (in Chihuahuan Raven, rictal bristles extend significantly farther, up to 2/3 the length of the culmen), large size (compared to Chihuahuan Raven), long tail (compared to Chihuahuan Raven) and vocalizations (repeated deep, strong croaks and "knocking" calls, not the characteristic "quark" call of the Chihuahuan Raven).

Observation Details: For the individual in the photos: at first we saw the 'white' at the base of the neck and thought Chihuahuan Raven.  I think Common/Chihuahuan ID is more difficult than the field guides make it out to be.  In this individual the bill (and the whole bird) was very large, the nasal bristles come only halfway down the length of the bill, and the tail was strongly wedge-shaped, all like Common Raven.    Common Raven is supposed to have "pale silvery gray" bases of the neck feathers rather than "white" in Chihuahuan. In photos (especially backlit ones like these), how the photos are exposed and processed can make a difference between "white" and "pale silvery gray".  So I think we are seeing "pale silvery gray" here.  If this is wrong, I'd be happy to be corrected.

Observation Details: I was able to photograph two Common Ravens today feeding on one of three White-tailed Deer carcasses that the nearby landowner has placed in this field.  Two days ago, I spotted two American Crows and two adult Bald Eagles feeding on these same carcasses and let my fellow birders know to be on the lookout for possible ravens, since they had been sighted along this stretch of road multiple times during the past two years, including once with newly-fledged young (by Jennifer Ferrick).  So, after I notified my fellow birders two days ago, Robert Scribner came immediately out to this carcass site and saw two ravens feeding, and even captured a few photos.  I came back yesterday afternoon and saw nothing.  This morning there were these two ravens feeding alongside this adult Bald Eagle.  A second Bald Eagle was perched nearby on the tree line.  It was quite instructional to watch the interaction between the eagle and the ravens on the carcass.  The ravens were quite bold and even mischievous toward the feeding eagle.  One raven repeated walked up behind the feeding eagle and bit its tail (one photo shows this).  The eagle would spin around, spread its wings, and lunge toward the ravens.  They would flutter out of reach, then walk right back and start feeding again.  I saw this 2-3 times.  The entire 15 minutes we watched, all three birds fed on the carcasses, with the ravens being the less dominate, and slightly smaller birds at the carrion piles.  Notice the large size of the ravens relative to the eagle, their massive bills, shaggy throats, and odd head profiles.  I never heard the ravens vocalize the entire time.

This nest site is on private property.  We decided to check the nest site to see if any birds had fledged, as this was the first return trip since March when we noted an adult bird on the nest.  The visibility of the nest is impeded this year as the entire structure was moved to a position that made seeing anything sitting on the nest impossible without literally entering the structure and climbing up a ladder.  We did not see or hear any birds on the nest.  However, as I turned around, Ben was pointing at a bird directly behind us standing on some of the structure of an adjacent building.  The bird (photos) was obviously a recent fledgling.  The plumage appeared to be good with just a hint of the down feathers on its stomach area.  The bird was hopping and doing short flights, but appeared to not yet be ready for full flight.  We quickly exited the spot after taking photos.  We heard an adult call in the distance.  A few moments later as we drove away from the nest site we observed an adult bird in an agricultural field appear to grab some kind of food and fly down to an area that we presume the adults are using to keep the new fledglings safe and teach them to forage.  We will attempt to locate the family in the near future to determine the number of fledglings this year.

Observation Details: This bird is throwin me and friends for a loop. I am generally pretty good at telling corvids apart. I saw them fly to the dumpster and they were huge with a wedged tail. But, looking at photos, I am thinking, "are they just a larger than average AMCR who is very wet making their bill look bigger?" But, the curvature of the bill still extends more to the end and the way the feathers are washed away from their breast signify them being longer than a crows. They were also hanging alone, no one else around. But, many birds were soaked bald today. Asked some friends who also leaned CORA over AMCR or FICR. If someone disagrees though, please flag this for review, TY!

Observation Details: I originally recorded these birds as Chihuahuan Ravens. However, I just read an interesting article by David Sibley about the identification of these species and now feel they are Common Ravens. I thought the light color of the feather bases was diagnostic, but it seems they are grayish white with light color extending up the feather shafts toward the feather tips, not with bright white cutting sharply across the feathers as in CHRA. Also, head shape and nasal bristle length are more consistent with CORA.

I watched him fly off to make sure he didn’t see the plovers on the mud flats below …he flew right over them and continued his slow heavy wingbeats towards pleasure beach.

Pair calling and flying in springs area. Then we saw a single Raven fly to the neighbors roof, while carrying something in its beak. Then the Raven sat on the roof, and began picking apart a plucked carcass, looked like a chicken carcass. We were standing maybe 60 feet away watching the Raven through binoculars. The Raven was perfectly lit up by the sun. I suppose this could have been a carcass of some other kind of animal (like a skinned rabbit), rather than a chicken, but looking at it through binoculars with the sun lighting it up, it looked like a mostly eaten chicken carcass. A person in the neighborhood keeps chickens, but I don’t know if this is where the carcass I was looking at came from. And maybe this chicken was killed by a raptor, and then found by this Raven. It’s is impossible to know. After the first Raven ate the carcass for a while by plucking the meat off with its beak, there were some vocalizations between this Raven and a second Raven, a little ways away. Then the second Raven flew to the roof and landed right next to the first one. It looked like they were a friendly pair, because they were not aggressive towards each other.  After a moment the second Raven flew to the carcass and grabbed it away. Then after a moment the first Raven grabbed the carcass and the two birds tugged on the carcass until it split apart, and they each had a portion of the carcass and they both continued to pluck the remaining meat off the carcass as they sat on the roof.

Yesterday continued to hear juvenile yells off and on and to see sticks being carried into the barn.   Over one hour yesterday, there appeared to be 13 feedings of nestlings, highest recorded thus far, but that is assuming that each trip into the barn was a feeding.   Earlier today and now in late afternoon now, no juvenile yells heard, and no nest material carried. Arriving we found that the property yard, usually extremely clean, had trash bags and boxes somehow overlooked and left out.  For the next hour the raven tore everything apart.  He (I think it was the male) nibbled as he worked, seeming to eat small pieces of this or that (he does the same thing when working down in dumpsters). He was cautious but obviously experienced in tearing into trash.   A chunk of whole pineapple gave him pause and he totally rejected it.  A Ritz cracker box attracted him, but he was little afraid of it, but ended up carrying it around.  At least 6 chunks of food were carried off and cached in the immediate area around the barn.  These chunks appeared to be either pieces of pizza or something similar.  Nothing from the immediate trash effort was fed to nestlings.

Media notes: Raven recovered 4 identical pieces of deep-fried meat that was fed upon and cached. This piece was  fed on for about 2 minutes before being cached..
Observation Details: Incubation.  Raven was at its usual morning dumpster when I arrived.  This dumpster is about 1225 feet from the nest in straight line flight.  I stayed 200-250 feet away to watch from my car.  The raven was down inside the dumpster when I arrived.  It brought out a round piece of deep-fried meat (photo), possibly Karaage (as best could be determined by finding a small piece later).  Over the next 10 minutes the raven had retrieved 3 more identical pieces, one at a time.  Each one was fed on briefly, then cached before retrieving the next one. Exception was the second one that was fed on for 2 minutes, then cached.   Raven left, starlings took over the dumpster.    Obviously the raven was being highly selective in its food choice this morning.

Observation Details: We soon made it to my favourite part of the day for a late lunch—Biscuit Basin. Although it was still raining, we braved it outside to make sandwiches and enjoyed them inside. However, I still stayed outside to enjoy a curious raven who claimed the picnic table in front of us. This curious raven popped its head up and walked around the table and the adjacent tree, waiting for us to finish our sandwiches to snatch them up. Behind this sentimental raven which I named Cheeto, multiple geysers erupted in the rain. The raven expertly posed in front of the geysers creating a chaotic scene. I spent a long time with Cheeto, long enough to become decent friends. We wished each other the best until we meet again and he flew up, out and over the river before he vanished into the geyser smoke. Until we meet again, buddy.

Observation Details: C.  Upon arrival, 2 ravens were sitting together in favorite tree.  One appeared to mount the second, but probably not successfully.  Then we realized there were 2 more ravens in the immediate area.   We assumed the 2 extra birds were the 2  fledglings from last year.  With binocs, we could see what looked like a yellowish gape.  The  pictures below show this and also show what appears to be a pale eye, all suggesting SY birds by appearance.  Behaviors of the adults and young suggest the same.  Twice an adult flew in with food, and we think the food was just put down and the youngsters ate it on their own. Once they  wing-quivered as the adult landed.  Many odd vocalizations between these birds, one of which was a lower, quieter croak with a strangled sound to it.  We saw no bird fly to the nest this morning.   On 11/16/18 we saw 3 ravens together at the Massey Building area, and similarly on 12/12/18, over Ashby Pond, and we wondered if it was the Willcox pair with one of their young from last year, but this is the first time we had any birds other than adults in the nest area since last summer.  We find it interesting that in this harsh weather just ending that the adults might supply food to the SY birds.
A pair were eating a small piece of meat, which could have been a rat.

I was driving east along Park Road when I saw a Black Vulture with four Common Ravens at some roadkill.  They all flew, one raven carrying some carrion dangling from its bill.  I pulled over to look around and saw two in the nearby trees.  After a couple of minutes one of the ravens flew out of the tree, right over my head (within five feet!) and down to the roadkill.  Another Common Raven started vocalizing from beyond the tree line and the raven at the roadkill flew back to the trees (I got a few close photos first).  Not the actions of an adult Common Raven.  At least one of the Common Ravens had pinkish-red inside the mouth indicating a young bird, but not necessarily a hatch-year bird.  Probably the same four seen within one hundred meters of here on June 18.
Building life/historical list.  Large bill, long pointed wings, flat head

Also the base of the feathers on the throat are pale gray rather than white (compare with the white droppings next to the bird).  ... The habitat (high up Mt Lemmon) also makes it far more likely to get a Common Raven. I also found other pictures of Common Raven, taken well outside Chihuahan Raven range, on MacAulay library that display similarly grey neck feathers.

This bird is throwin me and friends for a loop. I am generally pretty good at telling corvids apart. I saw them fly to the dumpster and they were huge with a wedged tail. But, looking at photos, I am thinking, "are they just a larger than average AMCR who is very wet making their bill look bigger?" But, the curvature of the bill still extends more to the end and the way the feathers are washed away from their breast signify them being longer than a crows. They were also hanging alone, no one else around. But, many birds were soaked bald today. Asked some friends who also leaned CORA over AMCR or FICR. If someone disagrees though, please flag this for review, TY!

Un ejemplar llegó procedente del norte, venía siendo perseguido por Tyrannus melancholicus, por lo que vocalizaba en vuelo. Dio un giro y se detuvo en un pino cercano, donde después de unos minutos, entre que vocalizaba y se arreglaba el plumaje, voló a una roca y comenzó a comer de algo que estaba ahí, espantando a un Coragyps atratus que estaba cercano, probablemente una presa en descomposición. Mientras hacía eso, un segundo ejemplar apareció en la misma dirección, norte y se reunieron alejándose de la zona. En diciembre de 2023 vi dos ejemplares en Roble Negro, San Fernando, Morazán, pero no pude documentar la observación y por tanto el registro no ha sido aprobado como publico. (https://ebird.org/checklist/S155944968). Al igual que en Roble Negro, los residentes manifestaron que es ocasional verlos y escucharlos en la zona (Bailadero del Diablo, Llano del Muerto, Rancho Quemado, Sabanetas). Esta es la primera documentación con fotografías y grabaciones para el departamento de Morazán y la primera documentación con fotos para El Salvador en eBird. Observation Details: For the individual in the photos: at first we saw the 'white' at the base of the neck and thought Chihuahuan Raven.  I think Common/Chihuahuan ID is more difficult than the field guides make it out to be.  In this individual the bill (and the whole bird) was very large, the nasal bristles come only halfway down the length of the bill, and the tail was strongly wedge-shaped, all like Common Raven.    Common Raven is supposed to have "pale silvery gray" bases of the neck feathers rather than "white" in Chihuahuan. In photos (especially backlit ones like these), how the photos are exposed and processed can make a difference between "white" and "pale silvery gray".  So I think we are seeing "pale silvery gray" here.  If this is wrong, I'd be happy to be corrected.

I was able to photograph two Common Ravens today feeding on one of three White-tailed Deer carcasses that the nearby landowner has placed in this field.  Two days ago, I spotted two American Crows and two adult Bald Eagles feeding on these same carcasses and let my fellow birders know to be on the lookout for possible ravens, since they had been sighted along this stretch of road multiple times during the past two years, including once with newly-fledged young (by Jennifer Ferrick).  So, after I notified my fellow birders two days ago, Robert Scribner came immediately out to this carcass site and saw two ravens feeding, and even captured a few photos.  I came back yesterday afternoon and saw nothing.  This morning there were these two ravens feeding alongside this adult Bald Eagle.  A second Bald Eagle was perched nearby on the tree line.  It was quite instructional to watch the interaction between the eagle and the ravens on the carcass.  The ravens were quite bold and even mischievous toward the feeding eagle.  One raven repeated walked up behind the feeding eagle and bit its tail (one photo shows this).  The eagle would spin around, spread its wings, and lunge toward the ravens.  They would flutter out of reach, then walk right back and start feeding again.  I saw this 2-3 times.  The entire 15 minutes we watched, all three birds fed on the carcasses, with the ravens being the less dominate, and slightly smaller birds at the carrion piles.  Notice the large size of the ravens relative to the eagle, their massive bills, shaggy throats, and odd head profiles.  I never heard the ravens vocalize the entire time.

Media notes: This bold Common Raven and another few frequent the picnic tables and Ramadas at the visitors' center. This one was sitting at our table just a few feet away when I shot this ... so close I had to zoom way out to get him/her in the shot.  Seasonal Park Ranger Sardius Stalker (great name for a new Harry Potter character by the way), who went out of his way to visit with us, told us how one of these birds have learned to sit on the visitors' center roof and spook Mourning Doves, which promptly fly into the window and stun themselves. Then the ravens make a quick meal of the doves.

2 seen and photographed entering area.  Found a big group (10) harassing eagles, then flying together towards the north.  Photos.  They called almost continuously while interacting, mostly with the "pop" type calls.  The first interaction I saw seemed like a pair perhaps in courtship, as nesting will certainly begin soon.  The other interactions seemed more like play, as the birds wheeled and chased each other, sometimes flipping upside down while pursuing each other.  After the group finished harassing the eagles, they worked as a group towards the north and slowly went different directions, sometimes in pairs, and a couple of larger groups.  I think that there were more than 12 there, but I went with the number I was certain of seeing.  Several birds were heard more distantly, but not seen.  In one photo, I was able to get 4 birds in the frame, but otherwise documenting the number was difficult as they were on the move the whole time.

Ravens visit the orchard and neighboring farms several times a year.  Their visits usually include a check on the free-range chicken wagon.  When chickens lay eggs outside of the wagon ravens find them and fly away with them.  Apparently these sharp eyed corvids spotted the unusually large eagle. Five minutes after the Golden Eagle landed on top of the cell tower the ravens appeared.  They wanted a closer look at the eagle.  Their inspection was silent and did not include chasing or harassment.

Observation Details: I originally recorded these birds as Chihuahuan Ravens. However, I just read an interesting article by David Sibley about the identification of these species and now feel they are Common Ravens. I thought the light color of the feather bases was diagnostic, but it seems they are grayish white with light color extending up the feather shafts toward the feather tips, not with bright white cutting sharply across the feathers as in CHRA. Also, head shape and nasal bristle length are more consistent with CORA.
